# TypeScript and JavaScript code style

In-source comments and TSDoc: see **`comments.mdc`**. READMEs and `docs/`: see **`documentation.mdc`**.

- **Indentation** — 4 spaces; never tabs
- **Semicolons** — terminate statements with semicolons; never rely on ASI or omit optional semicolons
- **Function keyword spacing** — no space between `function` and `(`: `function foo()` and `function()`, not `function foo ()`
- **Imports first** — all import statements at the top of the file, before any other code, unless there is a special reason (dynamic import, circular dependency workaround)
- **Import paths** — use relative paths within `src/`; use `@/` alias for imports from project root `src/` when crossing major domains
- **Import order** — group imports with a blank line between groups: (1) external packages, (2) `@/` path aliases, (3) relative (`./`, `../`). Alphabetize by module path within each group
- **Prefer traditional object-oriented structures** — use classes with explicit access modifiers (`public`, `private`, `protected`) rather than object literals for namespaced logic
- Prefer `switch` statements over `else-if` chains when checking the same variable
- Use braces `{ }` for all control structures, even single-line blocks
- **Explicit access** — all class properties and methods must have explicit access modifiers
- **Trailing commas** — when list elements are written one per line, put a comma after the last item. Single-line lists may omit the trailing comma

## Type safety and assertions

- Prefer the type checker over escape hatches; do not use `as any` to silence errors.
- When a cast is unavoidable, use a named target: discriminated unions, domain types, `satisfies`, `Extract<…>`, or `value as unknown as SpecificType` — never `as any`.
- In tests, apply the same standard: narrowing, `Partial<T>` with `as unknown as T`, or small test-only interfaces instead of `any`.

## Property syntax (accessors)

- Prefer TypeScript `get` / `set` accessors over `getFoo()` / `setFoo()` when the member behaves like a property
- **Pairing** — place getter and setter back-to-back when both exist
- **Backing fields** — use `_name` only when backing a public property accessor of the same name; otherwise no leading underscore on fields
- Keep ordinary methods when the operation is not a simple property (multiple parameters, async, imperative actions)

## File endings

- Files must end with exactly one newline character after the last content line
- Do not include two blank lines at the end of files

## Error handling

- Prefer returning `null` over throwing or logging for recoverable/expected failures
- Parsing methods should return `T | null` instead of throwing
- Never use exceptions or `console.error`/`console.warn` for expected failure cases
- **try/catch only for exceptional behaviour** — for expected conditions, check and return/set state; do not throw or log

## Module organization and barrel files

- Use barrel files (`index.ts`) for directories with 3+ related exports
- Import from barrel files instead of deep individual file paths when a barrel exists
- Do not export internal helpers from barrel files
